ected world. Whereas previous examinations of Buddhism in North America have assumed a more or less essentialized and homogeneous "American" culture, the essays in this volume offer a corrective, situating American Buddhist groups within the framework of globalized cultural flows, while exploring the effects of local forces. Contributors examine regionalism within American Buddhisms, Buddhist identity and ethnicity as academic typologies, Buddhist modernities, the secularization and hybridization of Buddhism, Buddhist fiction, and Buddhist controversies involving the Internet, among other issues.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 0aBuddhismzUnited States. 4aAmerican Studies : American Culture. 4aAmerican Studies : American Studies. 4aReligion and Spirituality : American Religion. 4aReligion and Spirituality : Buddhism. 4aReligion and Spirituality : Religion. 7aRELIGION / Buddhism / General (see also PHILOSOPHY / Buddhist).2bisacsh1 aAma, Michihiro, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBaroni, Helen J., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBeek, Kimberly, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBraun, Erik, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aChandler, Jeannine, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHickey, Wakoh Shannon, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMcmahan, David L., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMitchell, Scott A., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMitchell, Scott A., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aNiculescu, Mira, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPayne, Richard K., econtributor.4c